Local Engagement as a Countermeasure Against Populism
PARIS – The parties once dominating the Western democracies were shaken at their core.
Many – among others in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing electoral defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of U.S. President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former president Ronald Reagan.
These developments are similar everywhere in the West.
The tours of the once-dominant parties swing between denial and despair, while populists fish out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their supporters of their opponents as "regrettable," just as Hillary Clinton did shortly before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too terrified by the populist wave to launch a counterattack.
But neither denial nor self-satisfaction will resolve the entrenched political situation.
The Progressives must reorganize, and this begins with a diagnosis of the shortcomings of traditional parties.
Part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the real issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the declining social mobility, the worsening environmental crises, the increasing geographic inequality, the tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that truly matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the vanguard.
Today, they are all alone in the forest and wonder where everyone has gone.
The social sciences could have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed off course.
The gap between her objective analysis of reality and the policies of the governments has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the increasing gap in income and other indicators between some wealthy, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
Yet until the government of French President Emmanuel Macron implemented it, no national head of government had yet introduced tax cuts based on residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of France's GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
The traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion institutes.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the candidates became the basis of Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct, and Macron promised to address the issue if he were elected.
At that time, Macron's stance made him a target of his opponents' jokes; however, the laughter died out quickly with the rise of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not sufficient.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists periodically distribute flyers and rally candidates.
That was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that sees democracy as a marketplace, consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this viewpoint, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and maintain power.
It's no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, the established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological advantage over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups capable of mobilizing people to the polls, organizing protests, and launching petitions.
But this model no longer works.
Today, citizens refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education, new demands for participation arose.
The voters want to be treated as political actors with their own rights, not as peasants in the chess game of others.
In addition, the governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
That is one of the hard lessons we had to learn during the two years we worked alongside Macron at the Élysée Palace.
The most important political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital transformations, and gender equality – do not allow for solutions solely by national governments.
These challenges require deep cultural changes and, in most cases, measures at the subnational and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the entry barriers for political participation, so that traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent advantage and solidified support networks.
Who can effectively navigate Google, Twitter, and Facebook does not need an old party apparatus that has existed for centuries.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just on the elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should function as an administrative "back office"; the "front office" should be staffed by people on the ground.
At La République En Marche!, we refer to this as local citizen initiatives.
These range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training courses for seniors.
In any case, the goal is to offer solutions tailored to local problems, thereby strengthening the communities.
Such projects should be considered today as indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer rewarding ways for political and civic engagement will be crucial to its attractiveness.
And as they daily demonstrate their reform policies "live," the parties have already prepared the ground for success on election day.
When voters refuse to listen to what one has to say, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that the traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win the people over.
Re-establishing the connection with the concerns of voters therefore goes hand in hand with adapting the party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive policies on the local level.
